    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I hear the terrifying weight of that feeling, and I want to validate how profound and isolating it is to feel like the \"you\" inside has simply evaporated. When the thing that gave your life color and purpose—the art—dies, it can feel like the rest of existence is just a hollow performance, a script being read by an actor who has forgotten their lines. It is a crushing sense of erasure, and I am so sorry you are carrying this invisible, heavy burden of being an empty vessel.\n\nYou are right to feel that the \"substance\" is gone, and that is a very specific, very deep kind of grief that words often fail to capture. It is not just sadness; it is a fundamental loss of self. Please know that while the art feels dead, your capacity to feel this pain proves that the \"you\" is still there, just in a state of shock and devastation.\n\nIf you feel like you are dragging this empty shell around, please consider reaching out to a mental health professional or a crisis line who can sit with you in this darkness. You do not have to perform the role of \"being a person\" if no one is home; sometimes, the bravest thing you can",
